1.scatterplot

Out[5]:
<Axes: xlabel='total', ylabel='speeding'>
In [6]:
#Inference: The scatterplot displays the relationship between alcohol impairment and the total number of car crashes. It appears that as the percentage of alcohol increases, the total number of car crashes tends to increase and it has high increasing at alcohol percentage in between 4-6

2.lineplot

In [7]:
sns.lineplot(data=df, x='speeding', y='total', marker='o', linestyle='-')
plt.title("Total Car Crashes vs. Percentage of Speeding Drivers")
Out[7]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Total Car Crashes vs. Percentage of Speeding Drivers')
In [8]:
# Inference: The line plot shows how the total number of car crashes changes concerning the percentage of speeding drivers. There seems to be a potential positive relationship between the two variables, indicating that as the percentage of speeding drivers increases, the total car crashes may also increase.

3.barplot

In [9]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6),dpi=200)
sns.barplot(data=df, x="abbrev", y="total")
plt.title("Average Total Car Crashes by State")
plt.xlabel("State")
plt.ylabel("Average Total Car Crashes")
plt.xticks(rotation=90);
In [10]:
# Inference: The bar plot displays the average total car crashes in each state, allowing for easy comparison. It appears that (ND) has the highest average number of car crashes.

4.histplot

In [11]:
sns.histplot(data=df, x="total")
plt.title("Distribution of Total Car Crashes")
plt.xlabel("Total Car Crashes")
plt.ylabel("Frequency")
plt.show()
In [12]:
# Inference: The distribution of total car crashes appears to be right-skewed, with most states having a lower number of car crashes.At range of (12.5-15.0)  in total car  crashes has high frequency

5.boxplot

In [13]:

plt.ylabel("Total Car Crashes")
plt.xticks(rotation=90);
plt.show()
In [14]:
# Inference: The boxplot shows the distribution of total car crashes in each state, allowing us to compare the spread and central tendency of car crashes among different states.
